{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_gaston_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583966/1910092201/0342.xml":{"full_text":"\u2014Porter Clothing Co.\ni\n1\nGreatest Shoe Lines\nIn Birmingham\n\u201cBoyden s \u201cPorters\nShoes with an assurance policy. We put our name\non one line and Boyden on the other\u2014we put our\nguarantee back of both.\nI With the Boyden line and Porter Specials you\nhave the widest price range, the greatest variety of\nstyles, widths and sizes in all Birmingham.\n$3.50 to $7.00\n1922-1924 First Avenue\nCULLMAN COURT\nTRIES BIO CASES\nKNIGHTS OF PYTHIAS GIVE A BIG\nBANQUET WHICH IS ATTENDED\nBY SEVERAL BIRMINGHAM MEN.\nNEW MAYOR TALKS\nCullman, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\nfall term of the circuit court which con\nvened in this city Monday morning of this\n\u2022week has gotten well started into the\ngrind of the business. The first case\nwhich was brought to the attention of the\ncourt was that of Winter vs. Ignatius\nPoliak to recover a large attorneys* fee\nfor services rendered in the famous case\nof Gunter Gunter of Montgomery\nagainst Mr. Poliak of Cullman. The case\nwas taken up early yesterday morning\nand is still in course of trial, and will\nconsume the greater part of today. An\nother very important case which will\nIn all probability take the balance of the\nweek to dispose of is the case of E. C.\nKinney vs. Wr. J. Oliver. This case Is\none of the biggest on the docket, and In\nvolves more than $10,000. It is presumed\nthat this will be entered upon as soon as\nthe Poliak case is disposed of.\nA banquet was given by Friendship\nlodge No. 33, K. of P., at the large ball\nin the Leeth National Bank building in\nthis city Wednesday evening. Large ta\nbles were laid and upon them was\nspread a most sumptuous dinner. The\nbanquet was given for the general in\nterest of the lodge and a number of\nspeeches were made by local members\nas well as those who were present from\nBirmingham and other cities. The chief\nspeaker of the occasion was M. L. Rob\nertson, recently elected mayor of Cull\nman for the incoming two years. Mr.\nRobertson spoke In the highest terms of\nthe order, and concerning his recent elec\ntion to the office of mayor, he said:\n\u201cMy election as mayor of Cullman Is\nthe triumph of law enforcement and good\ngovernment. The strict enforcement\" of\nall law\u2019s governing cases coming under\nmy Jurisdiction rests entirely with the\npeople who elected me. I can do noth\ning as mayor alone, and unless I have\nthe co-operation of the good citizens who\nhave seen fit to place me in this office,\nJ am powerless to remedy conditions from\n\u2022what they now are, but if I am given this,\nJ assure you every law shall be strictly\nenforced to the very best of my ability.\u201d\nAmong those attending the banquet\nfrom Birmingham were Past Grand Chan\ncellor Herman M. Beck and W. T. Parker.\nDies From Horse'* Kick\nWaycross, Ga., September 21.\u2014E.\nPrentiss Peabody, well known business\nman of this place, died this morning\nas the result of being kicked by a horse\nMonday in a runaway accident while\ntrying to save his wife and little girl\nfrom the horse\u2019s hoofs. Mrs. Peabody\nsuffered a broken rib. Mr. Peabody\nwas a well known church worker and\n\u25a0was a member of the national board of\nmanagement of the Epworth league.\nWe Wash\nWith Ivory\nSoap and\nIntelligence\nAll the\nTime\n\"Excelsior Wagons Cover\nGreater Birmingham/\u2019\n1 _os@\u00a3.-&\u00a9\u00aey\n222 loin phones 222\nl \"i -j\n\nWILL BORE FOR\nOIL AT DECATUR\nCompany has leased thousands\nOF ACRES IN NORTH ALABAMA.\nDECATUR SHOPS INCREASE PAY\nROLL\u2014OTHER NEWS\nDecatur, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nThe Central Mortgage and Trust com\npany of Birmingham will very soon\ncommence boring for oil and gas in this\nsection of the state. It is thought that\nwork will commence by the middle of\nDecember, if not sooner. Twelve wells\nwill be sunk on a line running from a\npoint on the Tennessee river a few\nmiles west of Decatur to Fayette coun\nty, this being the territory laid out\nby the company's engineers and geolo\ngists as being the richest In oil and gas.\nThis line crosses the Winston county\nline ^t Nauvoo and enters Morgan coun\nty near Hartselle.\nIt Is said that this company has al\nmost unlimited capital. It has already\nsecured oil and gas options on 30.000\nacres of land In Morgan county, 5000\nacres in Cullman county, 3000 acres\nin Lawrence county, 27,000 acres in\nWinston county and a large acreage in\nFayette county. Representatives of the\ncompany are now engaged In taking all\nthe oil and gas options they can get\non lands near the two Decaturs.\nFor a number of months since the\nfinancial panic swept over the country\nthe Louisville and Nashville railroad\nshops In New Decatur have been pay\ning their employes monthly an aver\nage of about 360,000. This month the\npayroll reached nearly 3100,000 and it\nIs estimated that next month It will\ngo over the 3100,000 mark. This 1b one\nof the strongest evidences of the return\nof prosperity to the Decaturs and to\nthe entire country.\nA branch bank has been opened in\nSouth New Decatur by the Commercial\nSavings Bank and Trust company of\nNew Decatur, and is already doing a\nnice business, although It was only\nopened Tuesday. At present the brancli\nis occupying temporary quarters In the\nstore of Speak Mobes. Later, it is\nsaid, this bank will build a building ot\ntheir own.\nNellie Elisabeth, the little 5-year-old\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. L. J. Kelley,\ndied yesterday at their home on East\nMoulton street after an Illness of a\nfew days.\nSeveral negroes and two white men,\nwhose names could Aiot be learned, en\naged 111 a difficulty yesterday in which\nDaze Garth, a negro, received two shots\nfrom a revolver which will likely prove\nfatal.\nMrs. Groenendyke, a widow 85\nyears of agej seriously Injured her right\niiip yesterday while milking a cow. She\nfell from the stool and the hip Is badly\nsprained. Her 'condition is regarded as\nquite serious on account of her age.\nThe I.end-A-Hand Bible class of the\nFirst Methodist church has a lively con\ntest on to Increase the class member\nship to 100 by next Sunday. There are\ntwo contesting parties, one led by S.\nH. Malone and the other by W. J. Nes\nbit. The party securing the largest\nnumber of members by next Sunday\nwill be rewarded.\nMr. and Mrs. F. J. Wood and Mr.\nand Mrs. E. T. Lewis of St. Petersburg,\nFla., arrived in Decatur yesterday in\na large touring car on their way home\nin the completion of a 3000-mile Journey\nby automobile. Among the places vis\nited were Niaraga Falls and New York\ncity. The trip thus far lias been made\nwithout accident and they report most\npleasant Journey. Mr. Lewis is a whole\nsale merchant and Mr. Wood Is a\nbanker.\nMiss Viola Callahan and Mr. Ben\nRiddle, both of Austlnville, a suburb ef\nthe Decaturs, were married yesterday\nat the home of Probate Judge Wil\nliam E. Skeggs, Judge Skeggs himself\nofficiating, Both bride and groom are\npopular young people of Austlnville.\nNegro Boy Loses Leg\nHammond, La., September 21.\u2014When a\nheavy frieglit train today ran over the\nleg of Andrew Wilson, a 10-year-old negro\nboy, he drew the stump from beneath\nthe wheels and wrapped it up in a rag\nwithout uttering an outcry. He waited\npatiently until a surgeon tied up the\narteries and dressed the wound and still\ngave no outward exhibition of his pain.\nWilson was one of several young negroes\nwho were Jumping on and off an Illinois\nCentral freight train which was moving\n\u25a0lowly through Hammond.\nGRAY TO WELCOME\nINSURANCE MEN\nState Insurance Department\nEarns $185,896.97\nWANT CORN OCTOBER 1\nAll Farmer* Desiring to Compete for\nthe Prl*e Contest* In Each Coun\nty Must Send Their Ex\nhibit* at Once\nMontgomery, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nActing Gov. Henry B. Gray, who will\nwelcome the national convention of in\nsurance commissioners to Alabama on\nSeptember 27, will also be present at the\nbreakfast to be given eastern members\npassing through Montgomery on Monday\nmorning next. Montgomery is making\nspecial effort to show the outsiders that\nAlabama as a whole Is glad to have\nthem.\nSecretary of State and Insurance Com\nmissioner Frank N. Julian will speak at\nthe opening session also, terming what\nhe will say as \u201cremarks.\u201d W. K. P.\nWilson of Mobile will speak the welcome\nof the insurance men of Mobile. Other\nfeatures will be the address of President\nJohn A. Hartlgan and response to greet\nings by Eugene A. McGivney, vice presi\ndent of the convention. There will be a\nreception for the ladies after the meet\ning.\nOn the second day there will be papers,\namong them one from W. H. Hotchkiss,\ncommissioner of New York, on \u201cSavings\nin Life Insurance by Limitation of Ex\npenses.\u201d The recent sensational work\nof Mr. Hotchkiss in his own state will\nmake what he has to say of great inter\nest. F. H. Hardlaan of Massachusetts\nwill speak on \u201cPresent Classification of\nInsurance in Various States,\u2019 \u2019and T. H.\nMcDonald of Connectlcutt on \u201cDiscrim\nination of Life Insurance Policies.\u201d F. H.\nMcMaster of South Carolina will have a\npaper on \u201cUniformity in Rulings and\nHow to Obtain Them.\u201d\nAn important matter of the convention\nwill be the discussion of uniform laws\nfor the regulation of fraternal organiza\ntions and casualty protection. It Is de\nsired that all the state have like laws\njust here. Secretary of State Julian and\nC B. Brown, who Is to become the sec\nretary early next month, join in the hope\nthat as many members of the legislature\nas can attend and hear these bills dis\ncussed. Alabama, as Mr Julian has often\npointed out, is in sore need of regulation\nof to* \u2666ratemal companies, some of which\nnee< reful attention. It is, therefore,\nurgent that the lawmakers who are to\ncome in become posted, as there will be\nan effort to put legislation in this line\non the books of Alabama.\nAmong the entertainment features of\nthe Mobile meeting will be a visit in au\ntomobiles to the home of Augusta Evans\nWilson, the author, whose books have\nbeen read by the people of all sections.\nInsurance Report*\nThe total earnings of the Insurance de\npcrtment of the state for the year end\ning December 31 was $192,122.95, with ex\npenses of $6,225.28, leaving total net re\nturns to the state of $185,896.97. Company\nlicenses produced of this $18,379; agents li\ncenses, $20,807.50, and premium taxes, $152,\n930.45. Since 1898, the net receipts have\ngrown from $40,088.12, indicating the prog\nress made in this line of service to the\npeople.\nThese figures are shown in the annual\nreport just made, Frank N. Julian speak\ning for the department and report cover\ning all details being transmitted to him\nby Maj. A. C. Sexton, deputy commis\nsioner. It contains detailed reports on\ncompanies examined, on rulings of the\nattorney general, fire marshal develop\nments, all receipts and expenditures, new\ncompanies admitted, and the business of\nall companies. It also contains the re\ncent report made by Mr. Julian to the\ngovernor, In which he reviewed the year\nand made a number of recommenda\ntions.\nCorn Prize*\nCorn for the prize contests in each\ncounty, with oats and potatoes, must be\nin the office of the commissioner of ag\nriculture by October 1, In order to be\nconsidered in the prizes that have been\noffered. A letter to this effect is being\nsent out by Commissioner Wilkinson,\nthe only exception being that late, or\nfall corn, may be delayed as long as Is\nnecessary to get good samples. Irish\npotato samples are also eliminated, as It\nIs hard to get a good showing.\nIn his letter the commissioner says:\n\u201cThe time is drawing near when you\nmust forward to me samples of the crops\nfrom your acres of corn, oats, sweet and\nIrish potatoes. Please read our rules\ncarefully and comply with the same.\n\u201cIn case you do not fprward, at your\nexpense, samples of your crops, you will\nbe barred from the list of contestants,\nexcept in case good samples of Irish po\ntatoes cannot be found you will not be\nrequired to furnish these.\n\u201cThe department Is very anxious .to\nmake a good corn and other exhibits at\nour fairs this fall, and we request that\nyou send, not later than October 1, not\nless than 12 selected ears of corn and\none-half gallon of oats, and one peck each\nof sweet and Irish potatoes. Send these\nto the department by express, prepaid.\nFall grown corn, however, may be de\nlayed until such time as good samples\nare found.\n\u201cWe are exceedingly anxious to have a\nsplendid collection of corn for exhibition\nin this office and at the fairs, and we\nbeg that you will send not less than one\ndozen selected ears of corn so packed\nas to prevent shelling off.\u2019\u2019\nUnder the regulations $60 is given to\neach county to stimulate the improve\nment in crop production. For the best\nacre of corn $25 is given, for the best\nacre of oats, $15, with $10 for each of a\nbest acre of sweet and Irish potatoes. A\nmajority of the counties have taken part\nIn the movement and it is having good\neffect in the arousing of interest in all\nkinds of farming.\nYoung Man Hang* Him self\nNew Orleans, September 21.\u2014Believing\nthat he had creeping paralysis, William\nJ. Smith, a young dairyman, today slipped\na noose around his neck, tied the rope\nto a rafter in his barn and then leaped\nthrough a trap door. He was dead when\nfound by several of his workmen.\nASTHMADOR\nA GUARANTEED REMEDY FOR\nASTHMA\nSOLD DY ALL DRUGGISTS\nON THE MONEY-BACK PLAN\nDr. R. Schiffmanris \u201cASTHMADOR\u201d w>ver\nfails to give INSTANT RELIEP in the worst\ncases of ASTHMA. No WAITING for RE\nSULTS. Its action Is immediate, direct and\nCERTAIN, and a CURE is the result In all\ncurable cases.\nWE ABSOLUTELY GUARANTEE \u201cASTH\nMADOR\u201d to give IMMEDIATE RELIEP In\nthe most violent attacks of ASTHMA. So\npositively certain are we that it will do aaactly\nas claimed for it, that we have authorised all\nDruggists in the U. S. to\nRefund Your Money\nwithout question if It fails to benefit you. (1)\nSchiOmann Co.. Proprietors, SI Paid, Minn,\nPRICE DENIES\nFRAUD CHARGES\nBIG POLITICAL RALLY TO BE HELD\nAT CHOSEA SPRINGS\u2014BLACKMON\nAND ATKINS ARE WAGING STREN\nUOUS CAMPAIGN\nAnniston, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nMaJ. D. Houston Smith, assistant post\nmaster at Anniston, following clues se\ncured by Inspector W. L. Reid, is still at\nwork on the fraud cases under which\nLon Price, Sr., L. L. Melton, L. M. Mel\nton and Price A. Melton are In Jail here\nunder heavy bonds awaiting a prelimi\nnary hearing on September 27. He be\nlieves that there is evidence of a con\nspiracy and thinks others are implicated\nin the alleged frauds, as a result of\nwhich further developments are ex\npected.\nNeither Price, whose bond was raised\nto $3000 on Tuesday, nor the elder Mel\nton, whose bond was placed at $2000, has\nbeen able to secure his release from the\ncounty Jail, where they are confined in\nthe section set aside for federal prison\ners. They were seen in their cells and\ntalked affably in regard to the charges\nthat have been preferred against them.\nPrice readily admits that he has served\none term in the penitentiary for using\nthe mails to defraud, but he maintains\nthnt he is the victim of persecutors in\nthis instance, and intimated that he wili\nurt^ertake to shift responsibility for any\ncrookedness that may have been charged\nagainst him on M. L. Humphries, with\nwhom he Is said to have had business\ndealings, and who has been summoned\nby the government as one of the chief\nwitnesses. He also declares that his rela\ntives, the Meltons, were wholly disasso\nciated with his affairs, and that they are\nabsolutely Innocent of any wrong doing.\nComplaints are being received from\nseveral sections in the Anniston district\nIn regard to the premature blooming of\nthe cotton plant, due to the recent dry\nweather and other unfavorable condi\ntions. This has resulted in an Inferior\ngrade of cotton and is considered to evi\ndence a rhort crop.\nFollowing the report of the city court\ngrand Jury Tuesday afternoon, George\nJeheles, Will Carson, John Bowling and\nGeorge Lewis were arrested for alleged\nviolation of the prohibition law. Lewis\nfailed to make bond and was put In Jail.\nThese arrests follow the strong charge\nby Judge Coleman when the grand Jury\nassembled.\nThere Is to be a big political rally at\nthe W. P. Howell Memorial tabernacle\nat Chosea Springs, near Iron City, In this\ncounty, Saturday evening, when State\nSenator Fred L. Blackmon of Anniston,\ndemocratic nominee for Congress from\nthe Fourth district, will be the chief\nspeaker. He will be accompanied by\nJudge S. W. Tate and will read a letter\nfrom T. E. Kilby, democratic nominee\nfor state senator, who was to also be\npresent and make an address, but who\nwill not be able to attend.\nColonel Blackmon is planning to invade\nthe territory of his opponent at an early\ndate making three or four speeches In\nCleburne county, where his Interests are\nbeing carefully guarded by Hugh D.\nMerrill and Walter B. Merrill, who are\nplanning his campaign in that county.\nEIDLEMAH GOES\nTO MEET MR. TAFT\nCAPTAIN EDWARD TII.I., GALLANT\nOLD CONFEDERATE SOLDIER,\nDIES AT HIS HOME NEAR FLOR\nENCE\u2014MEMBER OF COMPANY D\nFlorence. September 21.\u2014 (Special.)\u2014\nDr. Lewis Eldleman of Mobile, who has\nbeen visiting Florence and who was\nnominated by the progressive republic\nan party of the First congressional dis\ntrict of Alabama, left today for Cin\ncinnati to meet President Taft by ap\npointment.\nCapt. Edward Till, one of the most\ngallant Confederate soldiers to go out\nfrom Lauderdale county In the Civil\nwar. died last night at 10 o'clock at\nhis home ten miles west of Florence.\nHe was 76 years old and had been ill\nfor two months.\nCaptain TUI served throughout the\nwar In Campany D, Ninth Alabama in\nfantry, with the exception of the last\nfew months of the war. He was\nwounded in the arm in the battle of\nPetersburg. He was engaged in every\nbig battle in which the army of Vir\nginia participated.\nHe was a steamboat man in his\nyounger days, running on the Missis\nsippi. Ohio and Tennessee rivers at\nvarious times and it was as a steam\nboat captain that he got his title.\nHe Is survived by hfs wife, formerly\nMiss Mary Brown, and by two children\nby a former marriage, E. C. TUI of\nFlorence and Mrs. M. Lanier.\nCaptain TUI Is the third brother to\ndie within four months and out of\n11 brothers and sisters the following\nsurvive himi James, George M., Miss\nKate, G. B. and R. W. Till, the latter\ntwo of Colbert county. The funeral\nwas held this afternoon at 3 o'clock\nat Canaan, the Rev. M. Malone of Flor\nence officiating.\nDEMOCRATS BOLD\nRALLY MEETING\nGadsden, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\ndemocratic rally here today was attend\ned by several hundred enthusiastic party\nleaders and was a pronounced success.\nThe two speakers, Congressman J.\nThomas Heflin and Hon. L. F. Greer, the\nfarmer orator of Calhoun, made an ex\ncellent impression and set the audience\ncheering repeatedly. Each of them spoke\nfor more than an hour.\nA large force of men is at work mak\ning the repairs at the rod mill of the\nSouthern Iron and Steel company and the\nplant will be ready to run next Monday.\nThe fires have been lighted in the open\nhearth furnaces and these will be ready\nto begin making steel when the plants\nresume operations next week.\nThe price of 13 cents for cotton seems\nto be small Inducement for the farmer to\nsell. While cotton picking is now well\nin progress there is little of it being\nbrought to market. Just now the senti\nment seems to be that the price must ad\nvance materially at an early day.\nThe Southern Stone and Marble com\npany of this place, owned by A. W. Cear\nley, who came to this city two years ago\nto engage in the marble business, has\nbeen sold to M. L. Gillespie of Boas, who\nwill take charge of the property at once.\nThe place is doing a fine business and\nIs in a prosperous condition. Mr. Cearloy\nwill make his home in Texas where he\nw(U engage In ft similar enterprise.\nCOUNCIL AGREES TO\nBUILD BOULEVARD\nHighway Will Connect Ensley\nand Wylam\nHURT IN RUNAWAY\nNr*. H. D. Barkley nnd Son nnd Mr*.\nS. C. Entreken Injured In Ensley\nAccident\u2014General New* of\nthe Steel City\nThe street committee of the Birmingham\nCity Council made a favorable report on\nthe proposed boulevard connecting Ensley\nand Wylam last night and a handsome\nhighway is assured In the near future.\nThis proposition was one of the articles\nof agreement under which Wylam be\ncame annexed to Ensley. This work was\nstarted before Ensley became a part of\nGreater Birmingham, but has been de\nlayed from time to time.\niAst Monday a meeting was held in\nWylam to protest against certain ma\nterials being used on the street, and the\ncouncil was petitioned to carry out the\noriginal agreement by building the boule\nvard.\nThe petition reached the committee yes\nterday and it wan unanimously agreed to\nbegin the work at once. The boulevard\nwill Join Ensley at Thirty-second street\nand Avenue E and will go through Wylam\nto the city limits. It will be 30 feet wide\nand will cost about $3000.\nPolice Court New*\nNo session of the police court was held\nyesterday morning there being no cases\non the docket for that day. There prom\nises to be a big court today as a number\nof gamblers were arrested.\nLieut. J. C. Jordan received a message\nfrom the sheriff's office yesterday to the\neffect that Walter Haines, who is in jail\ncharged with impersonating an officer,\nwras wanted in Cullman to answer a\ncharge of murder. No particulars were\ngiven but Haines will be held pending in\nstructions from the Cullman authorities.\nMrs. Nelson and Mrs. McFarlane, two\nwell-dressed white women, were arrested\nrested by Officers Henry White and\nSigsbee. It is alleged they are wanted in\nMemphis, Tenn.\nRunaway Accident\nMrs. H. D. Barkley, Mrs. S. C. Entre\nken and a son of Mrs. Barkley were se\nverely injured in a runaway accident\nyesterday. Mrs. Barkley was driving a\nbuggy containing the other two, when\nthe horse became frightened at an auto\nmobile delivery wagon belonging to H.\nW. Luther, the florist. The buggy was\noverturned and the occupants thrown\nviolently to the ground.\nMrs. Entreken sustained several broken\nribs and was otherwise bruised. The\nlittle son also had two ribs broken, while\nMrs. Barkley was severely bruised. They\nare reported as resting well.\nFortytwo Club Entertained\nThe Forty-two club was entertained\nyesterday at the home of Mrs. J. Hoke\nPerkins, on Avenue F. The afternoon\nwas one of much pleasure. Mrs. Perkins\nproved a charming hostess. Those pres\nent were: Mrs. J. C. Bryant, Mrs. J. F.\nLee, Mrs. Lothair Brooks, Mrs. George\nW. Crossett, Mrs. C. R. Walker, Mrs.\nC. T. Thomasson, Mrs. M. H. McDowell,\nMrs. C. J. Enochs, Mrs. W. H. Wynne,\nMrs. George Byrum, Mrs. Nat G. Clarke,\nMrs. R. H. Wurtele, Mrs. L. H. Pen\nnington, Mrs. G. E. Mohns, Mrs. F. O.\nHarris, Mrs. P. A. Eubanks, Mrs. C.\nW. Sharpe, Mrs. J. P. Barr, Miss Sarah\nGilder and Miss Bessie Morrison.\nLocal Items\nThe residence of Mr. Aderholt, Ave\nnue H and Twenty-fifth street, was en\ntered by burglars yesterday and about\n$75 worth of valuables stolen. The\nthieves have not yet been apprehended.\nThe ladies of the Wylam Presbyterian\nchurch gave an ice cream supper last\nnight near No. 4 commissary. The\naffair was well patronized.\nQuite a number of the Sunday school\nworkers of the Ensley district will at\ntend the county convention which will\nconvene today at the Cumberland Pres\nbyterian church on Fifth avenue and\n1\nEighteenth street, Birmingham. The\nsession will last two days.\nEnsley Personnls\nJ. M. Donaldson has returned from\nKnoxville, Tenn., where he attended the\nAppalachian exposition.\nJudge and Mrs. N. W. Scott have\nreturned to their home on Ensley High\nlands after spending the summer\nmonths at their summer home near\nGate City.\nThe little child of Rev. and Mrs. B.\nB. Glasgow Is critically 111 at Cope\nland's infirmary.\nMr. and Mrs. James Liddell have\nreturned from a tour of the British\nIsles.\nW. P. Boone of New York paid a bus\niness visit to Ensley yesterday.\nMiss Minnie Ryan of Meridian Is\nvisiting friends on Ensley Highlands.\nMr. and Mrs. J. E. Culver have\nmoved Into their new home on Ensley\nHighlands.\nW. B. Veal left yesterday for a short\nvisit to Atlanta.\nMrs. Gertrude Robinson, Mrs. Wil\nliam Robinson and Miss Robinson have\nreturned home after a visit to friends\non Ensley Highlands.\nThe revival services at the Wylam\nBaptist church continue to grow In In\nterest. The church Is crowded every\nnight. Last night six persons were con\nverted and Joined the church. Rev. Cur\ntis Shugart Is assisting the pastor In\nthese services.\nCOLLIER AND HARWOOD\nWAGE WARM CAMPAIGN\nVernon, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\ncampaign for the nomination for circuit\njudge of the Sixth circuit has reached\nthe joint discussion stage. It will be re\nmembered that Judge Collier was nomi\nnated at the regular primary election on\nMay 2, 1910, and that Judge Harwood\ncontested his nomination apd the sub\ncommittee trying the contest decided fav\norably to Collier, claiming that Collier\u2019s\nnet majority over Harwood was 7 votes.\nThe state committee, disregarding the\nfindings of Its sub-committee, ordered an\nother primary election for October 3, and\nthe matter will be finally settled on that\ndate. Collier and Harwood had a joint\ndiscussion at Sulllgent today and another\nat Vernon tonight. While it is admitted\nby all that each of the candidates is a\ngentleman of character and ability, it is\ngenerally agreed that Collier's superior\nability as a public speaker is having a\ntelling effect with those who hear him.\nHarwood carried this county on May 2\nby about 200 majority, but it is believed\nby Collier's friends that he will carry\nthis county on October 3.\nWAVE OF CRIME\nSTRIKES FRANKLIN\nTHREE MURDER CASES TO COME\nUP FOR TRIAL AT NEXT GRAND\nJURY TERM\u2014THE COUNTY HIGH\nSCHOOL OPENS\nRussellville, September 21.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nEvents which occurred yesterday will\nbring three murder cases before the\nFranklin county grand jury which meet\u00ae\nhere on the first Monday in November.\nYesterday morning Lina Mundine, a ne-\ngro woman, stabbed Bertha Martin, an-\nother negress, directly in the heart, kill\ning her instantly. The fight came up\nover one-half dozen eggs which the Mar\ntin negro had borrowed from the other\nabout one year ago. The Mundine wom\nan, after killing the other, came to the\ncity for the purpose of taking out a\nwarrant for the dead woman for hitting\nher with a smoothing iron, and she ran\nup to the deputies, who took her in\ncharge.\nArthur Jones is also wanted for hit\nting three negroes named Charley Crowd\ner, Jones Bolding and Jeff Ross, on the\nheads with the blunt end of an axe, from\nthe effects of which Crow'der died yes\nterday while on his way to Tuscumbia\nand Bolding will die. Jones escaped after\nhis work and has not been captured. The\nFoBter-Creighton-Gould company has of\nfered a reward of $10 for the capture of\nthe fugitive. The description as given\nout by the company is: Large yellow ne\ngro, weight, perhaps, 280 or 285 pounds,\nsix feet and four or five inches high,\nstout and healthy. The other case which\nwill come up is that of former City Mar\nshal M. R. Stansell for the killing of\nWilliam D. Berry.\nWith prospects all aglow for the best\nschool which has been held In Franklin\ncounty the County High school began its\nthird session yesterday morning with\nvery Interesting opening exercises.\nDr. G. W. Macon of Howard college,\nBirmingham, delivered an address to the\npupils, and his subject was handled with\nthe best of talent.\nFollowing are the officers for the ensu-\ning term: W. L. Yarbrough, principal: j\nMisses Orah Walton, Maude Forbes and\nLucille Sibley, teachers.\nFossie J. Weatherford of Burleson has\nbeen appointed a registrar of Franklin\ncounty to succeed Howard L. Blackburn\nof Vina, deceased. Mr. Weatherford\nwas appointed by Acting Gov. Henry B.\nCray without opposition.\na'I\nExposition\nE, TENN.\nGREAT ATTRACTIONS\njVDS\n\u2018ek of this great Expo\nof its large number of\nBand Concerts\u2014Pain\u2019s\nfright Brothers Aero\nkets on sale /fe p fiF7\nnited 8 days\nikets on sale /fen Qr\nited 10 days\nT\ni Railway\nservice and accommo\nppalachian Exposition.\nD.P.A. H. F. Cary, G.P.A. I\nM, ALA. Mill","height":"28168","width":"19468"}}
